public class RowResult

      • getObject

        public Object getObject(String columnName)
        Get the specified column's value as an Object. This method is useful when you don't care about autoboxing and your existing type handling logic is based on Java types. The Object type is based on the column's Type: Type.BOOL -> java.lang.Boolean Type.INT8 -> java.lang.Byte Type.INT16 -> java.lang.Short Type.INT32 -> java.lang.Integer Type.INT64 -> java.lang.Long Type.UNIXTIME_MICROS -> java.sql.Timestamp Type.FLOAT -> java.lang.Float Type.DOUBLE -> java.lang.Double Type.STRING -> java.lang.String Type.BINARY -> byte[] Type.DECIMAL -> java.math.BigDecimal
        Parameters:
        columnName - name of the column in the schema
        Returns:
        the column's value as an Object, null if the value is null
        Throws:
        IndexOutOfBoundsException - if the column doesn't exist

      • getObject

        public Object getObject(int columnIndex)
        Get the specified column's value as an Object. This method is useful when you don't care about autoboxing and your existing type handling logic is based on Java types. The Object type is based on the column's Type: Type.BOOL -> java.lang.Boolean Type.INT8 -> java.lang.Byte Type.INT16 -> java.lang.Short Type.INT32 -> java.lang.Integer Type.INT64 -> java.lang.Long Type.UNIXTIME_MICROS -> java.sql.Timestamp Type.FLOAT -> java.lang.Float Type.DOUBLE -> java.lang.Double Type.STRING -> java.lang.String Type.BINARY -> byte[] Type.DECIMAL -> java.math.BigDecimal
        Parameters:
        columnIndex - Column index in the schema
        Returns:
        the column's value as an Object, null if the value is null
        Throws:
        IndexOutOfBoundsException - if the column doesn't exist
